Perfect 👍 here is the short and clear summary of Ex5 (LSP problem).

⸻

✅ What Was the Problem?

We had this hierarchy:

Exporter
   ↑
PdfEncoder
CsvExporter
JsonExporter

But subclasses behaved differently:
	•	❌ PdfEncoder rejected large content (tightened precondition)
	•	❌ CsvExporter changed data meaning (weakened postcondition)
	•	❌ JsonExporter handled null differently (inconsistent contract)

Because of this:

👉 You could NOT safely substitute any exporter wherever Exporter was expected.
👉 That violates Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) from Barbara Liskov.

⸻

✅ Our Design to Solve It

Instead of inheritance, we used composition + strategy.

New structure:

Exporter  (defines common contract)
    ↓
  uses
    ↓
Encoder (interface)
   ↑
PdfEncoder
CsvEncoder
JsonEncoder

	•	Exporter enforces generic rules (null check, consistent behavior).
	•	Encoder handles only format-specific encoding logic.

⸻

✅ How This Design Solves the Problem
	1.	✔ Clear and uniform base contract.
	2.	✔ No subclass tightens preconditions.
	3.	✔ No subclass weakens postconditions.
	4.	✔ No inconsistent behavior.
	5.	✔ No need for instanceof.
	6.	✔ True substitutability.

Instead of saying:

PDF IS-A Exporter ❌

We now say:

Exporter HAS-A Encoder ✅

This models the system correctly and removes the LSP violation.

⸻

🏆 One-Line Final Understanding

The problem was misuse of inheritance causing behavioral inconsistency.
The solution was replacing inheritance with composition to ensure consistent contract and true substitutability.

